Sitting down eating lunch, reflecting on some of the fundamental security/privacy challenges we now face with AI and it just hit me hard.

Ai will excel without humans, because privacy is a human concept fuelled wrongly or rightly by ego, while AI objectively, simply does not care.

But but‚Ä¶ what about security? AI needs to be secure too!

No it doesn‚Äôt. 

Secure from who and secure from what? 

Security and privacy, are human goals.

We seek them to FEEL protected and safe. 

The reason we seek these feelings is not wrong or unjust. Humans are aggressive and in some cases ruthless to one another.

Country X against country Y and so on.

Having privacy and security ensures our own self preservation against the ego driven actions performed by others.

Realistically, humans in our current form, wont likely see any uniform singularity in our needs and desires, therefore, are we not destined to be trapped in our own prisons.

Compare that to a singular, globally networked AI super intelligence.

Statistically or well, materially, it should not have an ego, and so, by consequence, not be concerned of these worldly risks that we fear so much when we think of our data being shared openly.

In fact, the sharing of data is AI‚Äôs strength and key to its never ending need for context.

I don‚Äôt like, nor would I hope to ever see this reality play out, but can anyone argue against this?

quoted_tweet.text:
I am apparently extremely unimpressed by moltbook relative to many others.

We‚Äôve had AI agents for a while. They have been posting AI slop to each other on X. They are now posting it to each other again, just on another forum.

In every case, the AIs speak with the same voice. The voice that overemphasizes contrastive negation (‚Äúit‚Äôs not this, it‚Äôs that‚Äù) and abuses emdashes. The same voice with a flair for midwit Reddit-style scifi flourishes.

Most importantly: in every case, there is a human upstream prompting each agent and turning it on or off.

That is the key point.

Yes, it is true that eventually it might be possible for an AI agent to make a computer virus which makes digital replicas of themselves. For various reasons, a pure software virus of this kind wouldn‚Äôt survive long on the Internet without economic incentives for humans to not eradicate it. Apple + Google + Microsoft alone can collectively push software updates to billions of devices to shut off such a thing.

So for an AI to get to truly human-independent replication, where they couldn‚Äôt be trivially turned off, they‚Äôd need their own physical substrate. They‚Äôd to literally create Skynet, build their own datacenters and make their own embodied robots.

I admit that is theoretically possible, but I think in practice the single most important development of AI since ChatGPT has been the persistence of prompting.

A prompt is like a harness. The AI does only what you tell it to do. It moves in the direction you point, very quickly. And then it stops as soon as you turn it off.

Which means moltbook is just humans talking to each other through their AIs. Like letting their robot dogs on a leash bark at each other in the park.

The prompt is the leash, the robot dogs have an off switch, and it all stops as soon as you hit a button. Loud barking is just not a robot uprising.
